source: cli/tests/help.rs
expression: text
---
Userspace FUSE driver for btrfs, built on btrfs-disk.

Usage: fuse [OPTIONS] <IMAGE> <MOUNTPOINT>

Arguments:
  <IMAGE>
          Path to the btrfs image file or block device

  <MOUNTPOINT>
          Mount point

Options:
  -f, --foreground
          Run in the foreground (do not daemonize)

      --allow-other
          Allow other users to access the mount

      --subvol <SUBVOL>
          Mount the named subvolume as the root of the FUSE filesystem. The path
          is interpreted relative to the filesystem root, e.g. `--subvol
          home/snapshots/2025-01-01`. Mutually exclusive with `--subvolid`

      --subvolid <SUBVOLID>
          Mount the subvolume with this tree id. Use the value reported by
          `btrfs subvolume list`. Mutually exclusive with `--subvol`

      --no-default-permissions
          Don't ask the kernel to enforce file mode/uid/gid permissions against
          the calling user. By default the FUSE mount uses `default_permissions`
          so a non-root mounter can't read root- owned files in the image —
          matching kernel btrfs semantics. Pass this flag to bypass that check,
          e.g. when inspecting an image whose stored ownership doesn't match
          your local UIDs

      --cache-tree-blocks <CACHE_TREE_BLOCKS>
          Number of tree blocks to cache (~16 KiB each). Default 4096 (~64 MiB).
          Set to 1 to effectively disable; large values trade RAM for fewer disk
          reads on tree walks
          
          [default: 4096]

      --cache-inodes <CACHE_INODES>
          Number of parsed inode items to cache. Default 4096
          
          [default: 4096]

      --cache-extent-maps <CACHE_EXTENT_MAPS>
          Number of per-inode extent maps to cache. Default 1024. Each map is
          one entry per `EXTENT_DATA` item in the file
          
          [default: 1024]

  -h, --help
          Print help

  -V, --version
          Print version
